  <slide>
    <title>History of IT Accessibility at DRES</title>
    <contents>

      <h2>Selected Highlights</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1995: Assistive Technology lab at DRES with hours restricted to building hours.</li>
        <li>1997: Created assistive technology rooms in 4 libraries across campus available during library hours.</li>
        <li>2003: Accessible publishing Wizard for Microsoft Word and Powerpoint.</li>
        <li>2004: Functional Accessibility Evaluator (FAE) 1.0 released for free use by anyone.</li>
        <li>2010: FAE 1.1 released for free use by anyone.</li>
        <li>2010: AInspector Sidebar for Firefox released.</li>
        <li>2014: FAE 2.0 released for free use by anyone and made open source.</li>
        <li>2016: AInspector WCAG for Firefox released.</li>
        <li>2017: First global accessibility awareness day event at Illinois.</li>
        <li>2018: A11lyFirst enhancements to CKEditor released to help people create accessible web content.</li>
        <li>2020: Relased SkipTo script for websites to implement WCAG requirement for ByPass blocks.</li>
        <li>2021: Released SkipTo Browser Extension for Firefox and Chrome to provide keyboard navigation to landmarks and headings.</li>
      </ul>
    </contents>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Contributing to Web Standards</title>
    <contents>

      <p>Just like the contributions DRES made to the Uniform Federal Accessibility Standards (UFAS) to make buildings and transportation systems accessible, DRES has contributed over half of the examples in the ARIA Authoring Practices to make the web accessible.</p>

